=09
		<h1 class=3D"uk-article-title">
					Your Guide To Understanding The Golf Handicap System			</h1>
=09
=09
=09
=09
=09
		=09
<p>If you=E2=80=99re a golfer, you probably know about handicaps. You might=
 even have a guess about your own handicap. But, if you=E2=80=99re like mos=
t golfers, you have no idea how a handicap is actually calculated.</p>
<p>Knowing how to calculate a golf handicap is an important skill for any s=
erious golfer. In this article, we=E2=80=99ll tell you everything you need =
to know about the golf handicap system.</p>
<h3>What is a Golf Handicap?</h3>
<p>A golf handicap is a number which represents a golfer=E2=80=99s ability =
based on their previous golf scores. It=E2=80=99s a way to compare yourself=
 to other golfers and track your progress.</p>
<p>Specifically, your handicap is a number between zero and 28 if you=E2=80=
=99re a man and between zero and 36 if you=E2=80=99re a woman. The number r=
epresents how many strokes over par you should score on a neutral course.</=
p>
<h3>How Does the Golf Handicap System Work?</h3>
<p>The golf handicap system is somewhat complicated and strange, but it=E2=
=80=99s easy to understand with a little patience.</p>
<p>Because you can=E2=80=99t have more than one handicap, the number doesn=
=E2=80=99t depend on the individual golf course. Whether you normally play =
easy courses or difficult courses, you only have one handicap.</p>
<p><strong>So how is your handicap calculated?</strong></p>
<p>First, there are a few important numbers to remember: Course rating, slo=
pe rating, and equitable stroke control.</p>
<p>The course rating is dependent on the golf course you=E2=80=99re playing=
 on. It=E2=80=99s what a hypothetical zero handicap player (a scratch playe=
r) should score on the course in 18 holes.</p>
<p>The slope rating is a measure of the difference in expected score betwee=
n a bogey player and a scratch player.</p>
<p>And the equitable stroke control is your score; however, slight modifica=
tions are made so that a single bad hole doesn=E2=80=99t ruin it.</p>
<p>For a single round of golf, you calculate your =E2=80=9Chandicap differe=
ntial=E2=80=9D by taking your equitable stroke control, subtracting the cou=
rse rating, then multiplying that result by 113, and finally, dividing it a=
ll by the course=E2=80=99s slope rating.</p>
<p>But that=E2=80=99s your handicap differential, not your handicap. Bare w=
ith me; we=E2=80=99re almost there.</p>
<p>Once you=E2=80=99ve calculated your handicap differential for five diffe=
rent rounds, your official handicap is your lowest single handicap differen=
tial. If you have more than twenty official rounds under your belt, then yo=
ur handicap is the average of your lowest 10 handicap differentials.</p>
<p>But you don=E2=80=99t need to worry about all the details.</p>
<p>If you=E2=80=99re a member of a golf club, they probably offer a handica=
p calculation service. Or, if you=E2=80=99re just curious, you can use an o=
nline handicap calculator.</p>
<h3>How Do You Use Your Handicap?</h3>
<p>Now that you have your handicap, you can use it to calculate your net sc=
ore next time you go golfing.</p>
<p>To do this, you need to find your course handicap, which is your handica=
p multiplied by the course=E2=80=99s slope rating then divided by 113. Then=
, your net score is simply your score minus your course handicap.</p>
<p>You can compare this net score to the course rating to get an idea of ho=
w well you played.</p>
<h3>Lower Your Golf Handicap</h3>
<p>Now that you understand what your golf handicap is, it=E2=80=99s time to=
 get out there and lower it.</p>
<p>There=E2=80=99s no better way to improve your game than by playing. Visi=
t Blue Sky Golf Club in Jacksonville and get out there today!</p> =09
